title: Dams, North Korea Uncovered
name: Dams, North Korea Uncovered
description:
This Google Earth project offers an extensive mapping of North Korea's economic, cultural, political, and military infrastructures. Through the topic menu, users of this program have easy access to geographical information on North Korea's agriculture projects, aviation facilities, communications, hospitals, hotels, energy infrastructure, financial services, leisure destinations, manufacturing facilities, markets, mines, religious locations, restaurants, schools, and transportation infrastructure. In addition to locations of economic interest, this map also displays anti-aircraft locations, the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) and Northern Line Limit Line (NLL), incarceration facilities, political monuments, political residencies, military bases, and nuclear facilities.

This is an individual kml file taken from the original for Dams in North Korea.

What Happened to the Secretary of Propaganda and Agitation Department, Jeong Ha Choel?

The ceremony for the completion of Samsoo Power Plant was held in May of 2007. Chosun Central TV propagated this event under the title of “A monumental creation of the Military-First period, Samsoo Power Plant.”

The construction of Samsoo Power Plant had been discussed at the 5th National Convention of the Chosun Workers’ Party, in 1970. However, it could not proceed due to the inadequate quality of soil at the building sight. In the early 2000s, the debate over the construction of Samsoo Power Plant originated from a veiled feud between the Guidance Department and the Propaganda and Agitation Department. 

At the center of this debate is the rise and fall of the secretary of Secretary of Propaganda and Agitation Department, Jeong Ha Choel, and first Vice-Director of the Central Committee of the Party, Choi Choon Hwang. The rumor that Jeong Ha Choel has been purged from power has been circulating; however, the South Korean officials have not confirmed the rumor, and Choel remains listed as the Secretary of Propaganda and Agitation in the directory issued by the South Korean government. 

He has not made a public appearance since he participated in the 60th Anniversary of the Party and stood among other officials on Kim Jong Il’s Podium in October of 2005. He did not attend the formal military inspection on the 75th Anniversary of the People’s Army in April, 2007. 

On June 18, 1999, Kim Jong Il ordered the Propaganda and Agitation Department to develop the Samjiyeon area as a pretext to overcoming the March of Tribulation (period of mass starvation in the 1990s). The department mobilized approximately 50 thousand people in December of 2000 and organized the “Shock Brigade for the Propaganda of the Party Ideology.” The Shock Brigade for development of Samjiyoen was publicly launched on April 15, 2001. 

The Propaganda and Agitation Department intended to take back the leadership of the Party, a position they had been deprived of two decades earlier by the Guidance Department. After completing the construction of the Samjiyoen No.1 Road, Kim Jong Il’s exclusive road, Choi Choon Hwang made plans to implement a new construction project in an effort to gain the trust of Kim Jong Il. This was the construction of Samsoo Power Plant. 

Competitive relations between the Propaganda and Agitation Department and the Guidance Department.

In the 1970s, the Propaganda and Agitation Department had been acknowledged as the most powerful department in the Workers’ Party, as Kim Jong Il played a role in the art and culture projects implemented through the department. However, the power of the Party moved to the Guidance Department after Kim Jong Il became the secretary of the Guidance Department under the Central Committee of the Party at the 6th National Convention of the Chosun Workers’ Party. 

During the March of Tribulation in the late 1990s, North Korean authorities educated through the Propaganda and Agitation Department that the economic crisis occurred as a result of natural disasters and because of isolating maneuvers by enemies and imperialists. This propaganda was coined by the 1st Vice-Director of the Propaganda and Agitation Department, Choi Choon Hwang and the Director of the department Jeong Ha Choel. 

On account of their activities, they emerged as the most faithful associates of Kim Jong Il. Choi Choon Hwang accompanied Kim Jong Il during onsite inspections more than 40 times in 1999 alone. Moreover, he has never been excluded from one of Kim Jong Il’s private parties. 

When the construction of the Samsoo Power Plant was suggested by the Propaganda and Agitation Department, the Guidance Department tried to prove that the construction would be impossible due to the condition of the soil at the building site. 

Regardless, Kim Jong Il sided with the Propaganda and Agitation Department so as to encourage the people to strengthen their national unity. The ground-breaking ceremony of the Samsoo Power Plant was held in May, 2004 at the confluence of the Woonchong and Huhcheon Rivers in Jangan-ri, Hyesan and included 30 thousand members of the “Shock Brigade for the Propaganda of the Party Ideology.”

However the Guidance Department, led by Jang Sung Taek, the brother-in-law of Kim Jong Il had no desire to concede power to the Department of Propaganda and Agitation.. 

The flash point of the power struggle between the two departments was reached at the wedding ceremony of Choi Choon Hwang’s daughter in March, 2004. Many officials of the Party and the local party committees gathered at the wedding, competing in prowess, bringing around 1,000 US dollars each as a congratulatory wedding gift. This is a common occurrence at private event involving powerful individuals. 

The Guidance Department reported to Kim Jong Il that the wedding ceremony was so luxurious and Choi Choon Hwang tried to establish leadership through it. All the department participants were renounced for it, and the 31 officials who donated 1,000 dollars were expelled to rural areas. 

Choi Choon Hwang was fired from his post for one of the biggest crimes involving a power grab. In 2005, Joeng Ha Choel was also fired and imprisoned in the Deukjang Political Prisoners’ Camp in Bookchang, South Pyongan, which is a completely controlled zone. 

After the incident, Party power was returned to the Guidance Department

properties.name: Taegak Youth Dam
properties.description: Pyongyang, April 4 (KCNA) -- It is three years since the commissioning of the Kaechon-Lake Thaesong gravity-fed waterway of Korean style. It has provided at least 1.9 billion tons of water to more than ten towns, counties and districts in South Phyongan Province and Pyongyang. This is equal to the amount of water to be pumped by ten pumping machines with a capacity of 2 tons per second for three years non-stop. This waterway extending hundreds of kilometers from the Taegak Youth Dam runs to Lake Thaesong, filling 20 reservoirs with water and adding beauty to the landscape of the country. It has watered fields of co-op farms realigned as befitting the land of socialist Korea, while supplying industrial and drinking water to inhabitants. The construction of this irrigation system resulted in saving more than 300 million kwh of electricity as it was no longer necessary to operate at least 500 pumps, electric motors, transformers at hundreds of pumping stations. It was more beneficial than operating a power station with a generating capacity of tens of thousands of kw. There appeared along the waterway such big and small power stations as the Taegak Youth Power Station and Phyongwon power stations Nos. 1, 2 and 3 and this also helped the existing minor power stations increase their capacity, creating an additional generating capacity of over 10,000 kw.
